Key Findings

This section summarizes everything discovered during EDA.

1. Income Distribution
Most customers belong to the low and middle-income groups.
Only a small number of customers have very high incomes.

Business Finding:

The company should maintain affordable product offerings while also creating premium campaigns for high-income customers.

2. Age Distribution
Most customers are between 45 and 60 years old.
Very few customers belong to the younger or very old age groups.

Business Finding:

Middle-aged customers represent the largest customer segment and should remain the primary target audience.

3. Spending Behavior
Most customers have relatively low total spending.
A small group of customers contributes significantly higher spending.

Business Finding:

High-spending customers are valuable and should receive personalized offers and loyalty rewards.

4. Campaign Response
Customers with higher income are more likely to respond.
Customers with higher total spending are also more likely to respond.
Age shows only a weak influence on campaign response.

Business Finding:

Income and spending behavior are stronger predictors of campaign success than age.

5. Customer Purchasing Behavior
Customers who make more purchases generally spend more.
Purchase frequency positively influences total revenue.

Business Finding:

Encouraging repeat purchases can significantly increase overall sales.

Customer Segmentation

Based on the analysis, customers can be divided into the following groups.

Segment 1 — High-Value Customers

Characteristics

High Income
High Total Spend
High Purchase Frequency
More likely to respond

Recommended Strategy

Premium products
Personalized recommendations
Exclusive loyalty rewards
VIP membership benefits
Segment 2 — Potential Customers

Characteristics

Medium Income
Medium Spending
Moderate purchase activity

Recommended Strategy

Product bundles
Seasonal discounts
Personalized email campaigns
Limited-time promotional offers
Segment 3 — Price-Sensitive Customers

Characteristics

Low Income
Low Spending
Less responsive to campaigns

Recommended Strategy

Discount coupons
Cashback offers
Entry-level products
Festival promotions
Segment 4 — Inactive Customers

Characteristics

High Recency (haven't purchased recently)
Low purchase frequency

Recommended Strategy

Win-back campaigns
Reminder emails
Special reactivation discounts
Personalized recommendations

 Business Recommendations
Recommendation 1

Focus future marketing campaigns on high-income and high-spending customers, as they have the highest likelihood of responding.

Recommendation 2

Develop personalized marketing campaigns instead of sending identical promotions to all customers.

Recommendation 3

Introduce loyalty programs to retain high-value customers and encourage repeat purchases.

Recommendation 4

Offer discounts and promotional coupons to low-spending customers to increase engagement.

Recommendation 5

Launch re-engagement campaigns for customers with high recency to encourage them to return.

Recommendation 6

Use customer segmentation based on Income, Total Spend, Purchase Frequency, and Recency for more effective marketing.


Key Performance Indicators (KPIs)

To provide a quick summary of customer behavior and campaign performance, the following Key Performance Indicators (KPIs) were calculated and displayed in the Streamlit dashboard.

1. Total Customers 

This KPI represents the total number of customers included in the analysis. It provides an overview of the dataset size and updates dynamically when filters are applied.

Purpose:

Understand the total customer base.
Monitor the number of customers after applying dashboard filters.
2. Average Income 

This KPI calculates the average annual income of all customers.

Purpose:

Measure the overall purchasing capacity of customers.
Help identify whether the business primarily serves low-income, middle-income, or high-income customer segments.
3. Average Total Spend 

This KPI represents the average amount spent by customers across all product categories.

The Total Spend feature was created by combining spending on:

Wines
Fruits
Meat Products
Fish Products
Sweet Products
Gold Products

Purpose:

Understand customer spending behavior.
Identify the average revenue generated per customer.
4. Campaign Response Rate 

This KPI measures the percentage of customers who accepted the marketing campaign.

It is calculated using the Response variable, where:

1 = Customer accepted the campaign
0 = Customer did not accept the campaign

Purpose:

Evaluate the effectiveness of the marketing campaign.
Measure customer engagement.
Compare campaign performance across different customer segments.

  Final Conclusion 

The analysis shows that Income and Total Spending are the strongest indicators of customer response to marketing campaigns. Customers with higher income and spending are more likely to accept marketing offers, while age has only a limited impact. Segmenting customers based on income, spending behavior, purchase frequency, and recency can help the company design personalized campaigns, improve customer engagement, increase campaign effectiveness, and maximize overall revenue.